-Taking in Husserl’s Phenomenology -- tEnvy, Powerlessness, and the Feeling of Self-Worth -- tSocial Anxiety, Self-Consciousness, and Interpersonal Experience -- tTrauma, Language, and Trust -- tThe social world: empathy, morality, and metapolitics -- tEmpathy, Sympathetic Respect, and the Foundations of Morality -- tTolerance: A Phenomenological Approach -- tAnger, Hatred, Prejudice. An Aristotelian Perspective -- tHabit, Attention and Affection: Husserlian Inflections -- tDie äusserste Feindschaft: Heidegger, Anti-Judaism, and the War to End All Wars -- tHeidegger’s Metapolitics: Phenomenology, Metaphysics, and the Volk -- tIndex -- tErratum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe volume gathers together over twenty contributions that emerged from a conference held in in honour of Dermot Moran on the occasion of his retirement from University College Dublin. The book explores the contribution of phenomenology to empathy, intersubjectivity, affectivity, and the constitution of the cultural and social world, from both a historical and an applied philosophical perspective. Theoretical and methodological differences in approach notwithstanding, phenomenologists have converged in the recognition that self and others are fundamentally related, and have provided fine-grained accounts of the origin, forms, and implications of such relationship. The volume critically reconstructs and further develops central aspects of this body of research within a pluralistic framework. It offers a renewed investigation of the work of classical phenomenologists like Husserl, Heidegger, Sartre, and Merleau-Ponty, as well as an original application of phenomenological concepts and theories to contemporary discussions on intentionality, culture, emotions, and morality. The book provides insights for scholars in phenomenological philosophy as well as in philosophy of mind and interpersonal and social experience.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEmpathyxPhilosophy. 0aPhenomenology. 0aPhilosophyxSocial aspects. 4aEmpathie. 4aGefühle. 4aIntersubjektivität. 4aPhänomenologie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aPhenomenology.  aemotions.  aempathy.  aintersubjectivity.1 aBortolan, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBortolan, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrowell, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrummond, John J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFussi, Alessandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinämaa, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopkins, Burt C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInverso, Hernán G, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeane, Niall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLau, Kwok-ying, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Nam-In, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoidolt, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagrì, Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagrì, Elisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoran, Dermot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurchadha, Felix Ó, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNenon, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetherbridge, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRatcli